hivago<\/i> was rejected for publication in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Soviet_Union\" title=\"Soviet Union\">USSR<\/a>. At the instigation of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Giangiacomo_Feltrinelli\" title=\"Giangiacomo Feltrinelli\">Giangiacomo Feltrinelli<\/a>, <i>Doctor Zhivago<\/i> was smuggled to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Milan\" title=\"Milan\">Milan<\/a> and published in 1957. Pasternak was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Literature\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Literature\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Literature<\/a> in 1958, an event which both humiliated and enraged the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\" title=\"Communist Party of the Soviet Union\">Communist Party of the Soviet Union<\/a>, which forced him to decline the prize, though his descendants were later to accept it in his name in 1988.<\/p>","name":"Boris Pasternak","place_of_birth":"Moscow, Russian Empire","place_of_death":"Peredelkino, USSR","text":"Boris Pasternak , Literature, 1958 (forced to decline)","year":1958.0}